<TEXT>
rene acuna is starving himself to 
protest a life prison sentence but hes on a wellworn road that 
state corrections officials say will end in courtordered force 
feeding 
i am innocent and i dont eat said acuna a cuban immigrant 
who speaks broken english 
acuna 37 of detroit stopped eating except for water and 
sugared coffee march 3 after he was convicted of conspiracy and 
delivery of two pounds of cocaine his sentence is life without 
parole 
acuna once carried 180 pounds on his 5foot 5inch frame as of 
friday he had lost 64 pounds his body swims in his prison blues 
his cheeks are sunken 
i see the food like a chair like a sofa the hunger when you 
have a reason to support your spirit and your mind you dont need 
anything more he said in a telephone interview from the hospital 
at the state prison of southern michigan near jackson 
but a series of court rulings across the nation have upheld the 
power of prison officials to force feed inmates on longterm hunger 
strikes corrections experts say no record is kept of how many 
hunger strikes occur each year in american prisons but they believe 
long ones are rare 
typically courts decide that prison authorities need to control 
their institutions outweighs prisoners rights to privacy and 
control of their bodies said ed koren staff assistant for the 
national prison project of the american civil liberties union 
obviously they have an interest in controlling the institution 
and when a prisoner does something like this he is embarrassing the 
heck out of them he said 
department of corrections officials label acunas hunger strike a 
publicity stunt and have doctors check him each day 
the department will go to court to get the authority to force 
feed him if his condition worsens said leo lalonde deputy director 
of the department of corrections adding that could be today that 
could be tomorrow 
michigan officials seek such authority about 10 times a year in 
order to safeguard the health of inmates who refuse food or medical 
care said chris dewitt spokesman for attorney general frank kelley 
acunas lawyers say his determination poses an ethical dilemma 
this is the stuff la law is written about what do you do 
when your client wants to die asked james neuhard director of 
the michigan appellate defenders office which will handle the 
appeal of acunas drug convictions 
i told him if he dies from not eating even if he is innocent 
his appeal will be stopped right then said sandra girard 
director of prison legal services of michigan inc 
in a new hampshire case inmate joseph calk decided to starve 
himself to death rather than serve a 180year sentence 
arpy saunders calks lawyer said the new hampshire supreme 
court allowed authorities to forcefeed calk to keep him alive so 
that he could face another charge pending in california 
it wasnt up to him to determine how long he should serve 
said saunders summarizing the courts ruling 
mark david chapman sentenced to 20 years to life for the murder 
of former beatle john lennon staged a hunger strike to call 
attention to starving children 
but the appellate division of the new york supreme court decided 
prison security needs outweighed chapmans claim that the right to 
privacy includes a right to refuse to eat 
one exception to that philosophy came in georgia where inmate 
ted prevatte won a lawsuit to prevent authorities from forcefeeding 
him but eventually ended his hunger strike aimed at winning 
transfer to another prison system said department of corrections 
spokesman john siler 
the georgia supreme court found forcefeeding was too great an 
invasion of an inmates right to privacy saying the state has no 
right to destroy a persons will by frustrating his attempt to die 
if necessary to make a point 
</TEXT>
