<TEXT>
harvard university and its clerical 
workers union said monday they have reached tentative agreement on 
their first contract culminating 17 years of labor organizing and 
four months of negotiations 
the unions chief negotiator kristine rondeau said the pact 
would provide pay raises averaging 32 percent over the next three 
years 
its the prettiest contract youve ever seen said rondeau a 
former harvard medical school laboratory assistant who led the 
campaign that succeeded last year in organizing the 3500 workers 
over strenuous opposition from the university 
its got great economics and cooperative labormanagement 
relations and it addresses the concerns of working women she 
said 
former us secretary of labor john t dunlop a professor of 
economics at harvard led the universitys bargaining team 
the negotiators who had been meeting since february said they 
reached agreement in principle late sunday night the harvard union 
of clerical and technical workers is scheduled to hold a 
ratification vote thursday 
the tentative contract provides several new benefits including a 
50000 annual scholarship fund for child care and eight weeks of 
paid maternity leave 
it also gives the workers free use of the universitys athletic 
facilities increases their dental and pension benefits and raises 
the universitys contribution to their health insurance premiums to 
85 percent from 70 percent 
the union which is affiliated with the american federation of 
state county and municipal employees represents secretaries 
library aides laboratory personnel and mailroom workers throughout 
the university 
the effort to form a union among the clerical workers 83 percent 
of whom are women began in 1972 it culminated in a may 17 1988 
vote that the labor organizers won by 44 votes or less than 2 
percent of the total cast in the 15301486 decision 
harvard president derek bok a former law professor whose 
academic writings have been supportive of labor unions opposed the 
unions formation the university challenged the vote before the 
national labor relations board but lost 
bok said monday the university will work with the union to 
complete and sign the formal contract we look forwad with 
increasing confidence to a positive relationshp between harvard and 
the union he said 
rondeau said dunlop tried to foster an atmosphere of cooperation 
and goodwill toward the union in the aftermath of the bitter 
organizing battle 
i think he did everything that he could to change the way the 
university and the union related to each other and i think he did a 
good job at that she said 
dunlop was traveling to cambridge from new york on monday evening 
and could not be reached for comment 
</TEXT>
