<TEXT>
washington the latest oil shipping accidents in us waters are 
raising the likelihood congress will widen restrictions on drilling 
in promising areas off the shores of alaska california and other 
states oil industry analysts and lawmakers say 
the house appropriations committee is to consider wednesday a 
bill containing tough limits on oil development in the bristol bay 
area of the southern bering sea and in federally controlled waters 
off california new england and the florida keys 
rep frank pallone dnj predicted monday the legislation will 
pass the full congress this session in part because of publicity 
about oil spills over the weekend in the delaware river in 
houstons ship channel and near newport ri 
they just point out how delicate the nearshore environment 
is pallone said in an interview he wrote letters to several 
major oil companies earlier this month asking them not to bid for 
federal lease sales off the new england coast 
presidential press secretary marlin fitzwater said monday the 
latest spills show the pervasiveness of the problem but dont 
require new steps by president bush such as initiatives to limit oil 
exploration 
the latest spills were a significant blow to the oil industry 
which is still reeling from the devastating exxon valdez oil spill 
march 24 in alaskas prince william sound 
that accident the worst spill in us history almost 
immediately killed chances for congressional approval of legislation 
to open the arctic national wildlife refuge on alaskas north 
slope to oil and natural gas exploration 
a further consequence of the recent tanker accidents and public 
criticism of the industrys cleanup response may be a new ban on 
exploration in bristol bay a rich fishing area alaskas state 
government says is more vulnerable to spill damage than prince 
william sound 
theyll stop bristol bay exploration dillard spriggs 
president of the new york consulting company petroleum analysis 
ltd said monday its going to be hard to explore very much in 
alaska until the industry improves its public image 
although most of the capitol hill focus on offshore oil 
exploration has been limited to alaska california florida and new 
england movements to ban or slow down drilling have emerged in 
oregon washington north carolina and south carolina 
the oil industry long aware of political pressures to limit 
offshore drilling until recently sought to rely on its past safety 
record and assertions that less domestic drilling will mean more 
us reliance on foreign suppliers 
but since the valdez accident exposed the industrys inability to 
handle largescale spills oil companies have tried to take the 
offensive by promising to devote more money personnel and equipment 
to responding to major accidents 
the latest spills came just days after a special task force of 
oil executives announced plans to spend 250 million over five years 
to create a nationwide network of cleanup equipment and workers to 
handle a major spill on any coastal waterway the cleanup system is 
not expected to be working until next summer 
the american petroleum institute representing the major oil 
companies gave a muted response to the weekend spills it said 
although its proposed regional response centers will be designed to 
handle worse disasters the centers could have been called into 
action by the government if they had been in place 
the industry counters antidrilling arguments by noting that us 
dependence on foreign oil has risen sharply in recent years 
imported oil makes up about 45 percent of total us supplies and 
the foreign share is expected to grow unless major oil fields are 
discovered on federal land 
the industry and the bush administration say such reliance on 
foreign suppliers undermines us energy security and means more 
environmental risk from foreign tanker traffic 
bush is awaiting the recommendations of a task force he assembled 
in march to review potential environment damage from oil and natural 
gas drilling in federal waters off northern and southern california 
and the southern gulf coast of florida the group is to report by 
jan 1 
