<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that 
cbs inc no longer enjoys trademark protection for the amos n 
andy radio and television shows 
the justices without comment refused to review a federal 
appeals court ruling that cbs abandoned the trademarks when under 
pressure from civil rights groups it suspended commercial use of 
the shows 
the asserted trademarks were challenged by stephen m silverman 
who wants to produce a musical play based on the amos n andy 
shows and their characters 
the case now returns to a federal judge in new york city who is 
to rule on other aspects of the dispute todays high court action 
does not remove all legal hurdles confronting silverman 
the characters of amos jones and andy brown were created in 1928 
by freeman gosden and charles correll who wrote and produced the 
amos n andy radio program one of the nations most popular 
gosden and correll were white but amos and andy and all other 
characters portrayed on the program were black 
cbs bought all rights to the show and its creations in 1948 and 
broadcast it until 1955 
in 1951 cbs began broadcasting an amos n andy television 
show using black actors 
the television series also attained great popularity and a 
generation of tv viewers came to know george kingfish stevens 
his wife sapphire lawyer algonquin j calhoun and the mystic 
knights of the sea lodge 
the television show was aired on cbs affiliate stations until 
1953 it continued in reruns and nonnetwork syndication until 1966 
when cbs responded to criticism that the show presented a demeaning 
portrayal of blacks 
silverman in 1981 asked cbs for permission to produce a play 
based on a script called amos n andy go to the movies the 
plays proposed title later was changed to amos n andy in 
hollywood and finally to fresh air taxi 
cbs refused permission and silverman sued in 1984 
the suit alleged that cbs had no trademark or other exclusive 
rights in the material contained in the first 20 years of amos n 
andy radio shows 
us district judge gerald l goettel ruled for cbs on the 
trademark issue he said the network offered a reasonable 
explanation for its decision to keep the programs off the air and 
asserted its intention to resume use at some indefinite future date 
but the 2nd us circuit court of appeals last feb 6 reversed 
that ruling 
the appeals court said the trial judge misinterpeted the federal 
trademark laws handling of abandonment 
more likely congress wanted a mark to be deemed abandoned once 
use has been discontinued with an intent not to resume within the 
reasonably foreseeable future the appeals court said 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for cbs said other appeals 
courts have ruled that an outside cause for suspension of use of a 
trademark precludes abandonment 
the case is cbs inc vs silverman 881804 
</TEXT>
