<TEXT>
judges are adhering to federal guidelines 
designed to end disparities in criminal sentences the chairman of 
the us sentencing commission said tuesday 
more than 82 percent of the sentences handed down by federal 
judges fall within the guidelines in effect since nov 1 1987 
william wilkins said at a news conference 
he said his conclusions were based on a random sample of 25 
percent of the guideline cases handled over a 16month period ending 
march 31 
more than 9 percent of the sentences were below the guidelines 
and nearly 3 percent above it he said adding that more than 5 
percent fell below the guidelines because defendants provided 
substantial assistance to the government 
wilkins a federal appeals court judge said the system was 
working well and represented a dramatic improvement over earlier 
sentencing 
the commission was established because federal judges were giving 
widely different sentences for similar crimes the law enacted by 
congress in setting up the panel mandated that defendants convicted 
of similar crimes receive similar sentences 
critics have predicted that guideline sentencing would bring 
the justice system to its knees inducing an avalanche of trials by 
defendants who previously would have pleaded guilty wilkins said 
however he said more than 90 percent of the more than 7000 
defendants sentenced under the guidelines pleaded guilty 
</TEXT>
