candidate from altoona wis said cmdr dennis hessler public 
affairs officer for the naval education and training command 
that wasnt the case with the march 2 1988 death of airman 
recruit lee mirecki 19 of appleton wis who drowned during an 
intense rescueswimmer drill navy officials were secretive about 
investigations that led to disciplinary action against five enlisted 
instructors and an officer in mireckis death 
in this case it is sort of looking like theres nothing like 
that so we are being more forthcoming hessler said but he 
emphasized that everything was still preliminary 
fedie collapsed in shallow water while walking from a pool after 
an abandonship drill a navy spokesman said in the exercise 
trainees jump from a 12foot tower wearing flight suits and boots 
and swim 15 yards underwater to simulate avoiding burning fuel on 
the surface 
as early as saturday the navy disclosed preliminary autopsy data 
that indicated fedie died of acute cerebral edema a swelling of the 
brain and excess fluid that can be caused by lack of oxygen 
hessler said fedie was conscious after being pulled from the 
water fedie was questioned to determine if he was coherent and was 
able to tell rescuers who he was and give his class number hessler 
said 
in response to a question fedie said he did not hit his head on 
anything and the preliminary autopsy also indicated no evidence he 
had hit his head hessler said 
but fedie then went into convulsions and lost consciousness 
hessler said cardiopulmonary resuscitation and oxygen were 
administered at poolside before an ambulance took fedie to the 
pensacola naval hospital where he died 
fedie was a strong swimmer and had passed a physical examination 
june 9 hessler said 
one possibility is that fedie may have had a preexisting medical 
condition that failed to show up during the exam hessler said 
final autopsy results are expected in a couple of weeks but hessler 
was uncertain if they would be made public 
