with the 150th anniversary of the mormons settlement in nauvoo a 
town of about 1100 located 200 miles north of st louis that 
briefly was home to smiths followers the core of the church of 
jesus christ of latterday sains 
smith and his congregation arrived in nauvoo in 1839 when the 
town was named commerce 
they settled on 1000 acres in the swamp flats below the 
towns main business district the land was drained and divided into 
fouracre farm plots each member was given an acre for a house 
barn and a few animals 
within a few years a city of 15000 sprang from the swamp 
named nauvoo by the mormons from the hebrew for beautiful 
location it rivaled chicago as the largest city in ilinois a 
huge limestone temple was built on a bluff overlooking the town 
but the friction with outsiders that had forced smith to leave 
other towns followed the settlers into illinois 
mormons clashed with local residents who rejected smiths claims 
that he had spoken with god been visited by angels and was a 
prophet 
the conflict eventually led to the arrest of the smiths and two 
associates 
