<TEXT>
a nuclear weapons test that had been 
delayed by fickle wind conditions shook the nevada desert tuesday 
with an explosion several times the force of the hiroshima atomic 
bomb 
the blast registered 46 on the richter scale of ground motion at 
the national earthquake information center in golden colo 
according to spokesman john minsch 
monitors atop highrise hotels in las vegas 100 miles from ground 
zero registered the blast but the readings were not as distinct as 
with some previous tests 
the test codenamed amarillo was the second major us nuclear 
weapons test in six days energy department officials deemed the 
latest shot a success 
the device was detonated 2100 feet beneath the surface of pahute 
mesa on the sprawling desert test range and had an explosive force 
of up to 150000 tons of tnt the blast that destroyed hiroshima had 
an explosive force of 13000 tons of tnt 
the seismograph needle is swinging wildly from side to side 
energy department spokesman jim boyer said as he monitored the blast 
in a control center 30 miles from ground zero 
the test was originally scheduled for saturday then delayed 
several times because of unfavorable wind conditions it was 
rescheduled for sunday then delayed again for the same reason 
tests are not conducted if winds are blowing toward a populated 
area such as las vegas in the event that nuclear radiation escapes 
the underground cavity where the nuclear device is detonated 
boyer said monitoring equipment surrounding ground zero indicated 
there was no leak of radiation 
</TEXT>
