<TEXT>
a senate committee staff analysis concluded 
tuesday that running the controversial shoreham nuclear power plant 
on long island would be cheaper that shutting it down contrary to 
an analysis by state regulators 
after hearing some of the reports conclusions chairman peter 
bradford of the new york public service commission characterized the 
study which he had not seen as baloney 
the analysis was released as the nuclear regulatory commissions 
atomic safety and licensing board decided that it was acceptable to 
use polemounted sirens on trucks to notify nearby massachusetts 
residents of an emergency at the seabrook nh nuclear power 
plant the other completed but not operating reactor in the 
northeast 
though some of the truck sites would slightly exceed federal 
guidelines of that it should not take more than 15 minutes to set 
off warnings the board said the plan by the seabrook operators was 
adequate considering the fact that concerned political 
jurisdictions can reduce alerting and notification times by making 
sites available for sirens permanently mounted on poles 
the state of massachusetts and its towns in the evacuation zones 
have refused to cooperate in emergency planning and massachusetts 
deputy attorney general stephen jonas said the state would appeal 
the decision to an appeal board 
the senate report an analysis of a new york commission study 
performed last year of the plant owned by long island lighting co 
or lilco was prepared by an economist with the senate committee on 
energy and natural resources which is chaired by sen j bennett 
johnston dla 
his study concludes that the psc report is a biased and unfair 
comparison of shoreham inservice and the settlement johnston 
said in a letter to bradford the study shows that shoreham 
operation would save threequarters of a billion dollars in real 
economic costs over the first 15 years of its life 
the settlement refers to the pending deal to be voted on by 
lilco shareholders wednesday to turn the 55 billion plant over to 
the state for 1 and assurance of a decades worth of rate increases 
of about 5 percent a year though fully licensed the plant has 
never entered commercial operation local and state authorities 
contend nearby residents could not be evacuated in an emergency 
bradford said johnston assigned staff to go and find every 
fault that they could with the psclilco study 
the senate staff analysis concludes that lilcos electric rates 
with shoreham in service would average about 1522 cents per 
kilowatthour 029 cents cheaper than under the shutdown 
the state study estimated the average rate if shoreham operates 
sat 1496 cents or 052 cents more expensive than closing it down 
the report criticized the psc analysis for placing too much 
emphasis on electric rates in the first 11 years of shoreham 
operation while utility investments are typically analyzed over 
planning horizons of 2030 years 
thats flat wrong bradford countered the pscs study runs 
out to the year 2003 i believe but a lot of the further 
calculations run out over the life of shoreham 
the committee staff study also said among other things that the 
state had overestimated the savings to the company of being able to 
carry more debt with shoreham retired had failed to assign enough 
cost to shrunken generating reserves without shoreham and had 
assumed the implausibly low price for oil lilcos major fuel in 
the year 2000 of 15 per barrel vs 20 to 25 a barrel forecasts by 
private consulting firms 
