<TEXT>
the house on tuesday rejected a fiveyear 
extension of mostfavorednation trading status for hungary with 
some members arguing the issue should be left to the presidents 
discretion 
president bush already has announced he intends to extend the 
trade preference for another year 
the house vote was 242172 for the legislation less than the 
twothirds necessary to pass a bill under suspension of the rules a 
procedure generally reserved for noncontroversial bills 
during debate rep sam gibbons dfla chairman of the house 
ways and means trade subcommittee said the people of hungary 
have demonstrated since world war ii that they seek and yearn for 
freedom theyre close now it is time for us to take them off of 
probation and extend a helping hand 
earlier at a house foreign affairs committee hearing curtis w 
kamman deputy assistant secretary of state for european affairs 
said hungary had made progress in human rights including free 
travel and emigration 
hungary a communist nation in the warsaw pact will clearly meet 
the criteria for a new extension of its mostfavorednation status 
which presidents have renewed annually over the past decade he said 
in light of that there is no need for congress to direct a 
fiveyear extension he said 
countries in mostfavorednation status are guaranteed the lowest 
tariffs applicable to their products in other words they will be 
treated like the most favored nation 
speaking against the measure on the house floor rep ben gilman 
rny said the trade benefits should be left to the president to 
determine and pointed to the recent chinese crackdown on the 
prodemocracy movement as an example of how quickly situations can 
change 
gilman also hinted that president bush might want to make the 
announcement himself during a trip to budapest in about two weeks 
he asked colleagues not to preempt the president from taking the 
kinds of steps he would be inclined to do later on this year 
bush on may 31 announced his intention to extend hungarys trade 
benefit for another year 
the president also has generally held out the hope of increased 
economic aid to east bloc countries that expand freedoms and has 
promised a longerterm extension of mostfavorednation trading 
status to hungary if it passes a liberalized emigration law 
current law bars mostfavorednation status with its 
preferential customs duty rates to communist countries with 
restrictive emigration policies since the ban was imposed in 1974 
three nations have been granted waivers hungary romania and china 
