<TEXT>
the house ways and means committee approved 
legislation tuesday that would bar doctors from referring patients 
to testing labs they own but do not supervise 
the antireferral package pushed by rep pete stark dcalif 
is part of an overall medicare bill the committee is expected to 
approve on wednesday 
even though the section on referrals technically could be changed 
before the overall bill wins final committee approval committee 
staffers said it and several less controversial matters are 
considered final for all practical purposes 
the panel left the most controversial part of the medicare bill 
until wednesday the second of two days of closed hearings whether 
to clamp a limit on the overall amount medicare will pay for doctor 
bills and whether to adopt a new fee schedule for medicarecovered 
services 
the health subcommittee headed by stark proposed setting targets 
under which medicare doctor bill spending could not grow more than 
somewhere between 10 percent and 12 percent next year 
if actual 1990 billings exceeded that amount fees would be held 
down to compensate 
the antireferral provisions are aimed at removing the financial 
incentive for doctors to enhance their income by referring patients 
to labs in which their sole interest is financial rather than 
professional 
