<DOCNO> AP890627-0200 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
washington energy secretary james d watkins on tuesday 
launched a broad shakeup of nuclear weapons production pledging to 
chart a new course of environmental safeguards and conceding 
that a key waste storage facility has to be delayed 
the chickens have finally come home to roost watkins said 
after years of inattention to changing standards and demands 
regarding the environment safety and health 
watkins announced new steps for improving management of the 
weapons production complex including 17 major plants or 
laboratories in 12 states and for determining the extent to which 
the facilities are violating state and federal environmental laws 
he also said a new mexico site that was scheduled to open in 
september as the nations first permanent dump for waste from the 
military facilities would not begin receiving waste until sometime 
in 1990 he said he had no more specific target date 
we have had a flawed plan for opening the waste isolation 
pilot plant he said 
waste production has been reduced which should allow the 
production plants to continue operating normally until the new 
mexico site opens he said 
watkins announcement came as a group of 21 environmental 
scientific and church groups sued the energy department to try to 
force a broad public review of plans for modernizing the weapons 
plants 
the suit filed in us district court in washington said the 
department should be compelled to prepare a programmatic 
environmental impact statement a comprehensive analysis of the 
environmental and health effects of its weapons plant initiatives 
watkins declined to comment directly on the suit except to say he 
was committed to ensuring full compliance with all environmental 
requirements 
at his first formal news conference since taking office last 
march watkins said he was surprised and disappointed to learn of 
the depth of problems in the weapons program which has been 
crippled by mechanical failures and safety problems 
it has been a nightmare for me to unravel the background 
sufficient to make a decision he said adding that he was being 
forced to act on a crisis basis because of the urgent need to 
get key weapons plants running again 
three nuclear reactors at the savannah river site in south 
carolina which are the nations only source of tritium needed for 
nuclear warheads have been shut down for more than a year because 
of uncertainties about their safety watkins said he hoped to 
announce a reactor restart scheduled in july 
in what he called an illustration of the breadth of change he 
seeks in the weapons program watkins said the savannah river 
restart plan would require westinghouse electric corp which runs 
the plant under a federal contract to devote far more resources 
than our own program coordinator ever demanded in the past 
he said he was creating environmental tiger teams to closely 
examine each weapons plant to assess its compliance with state and 
federal environmental laws 
this is a complete review with my tiger teams moving out to 
see to what degree we have actually been complying with the intent 
as well as the letter of the law watkins said 
the departments increased attention to health and safety issues 
comes just days after the justice department raided the rocky flats 
weapons plant in colorado in search of evidence of illegal dumping 
and incineration of hazardous wastes 
watkins was mildly critical of justice for refusing to give him 
any information about its findings at rocky flats which makes 
plutonium triggers for thermonuclear weapons 
he said he wanted to find a new way of doing business in these 
events in the future if we get into this situation because i think 
its important that we know at once whether there has been any 
violation of the environment particularly when radioactivity is 
involved 
watkins said rocky flats illustrated the extent of turmoil in the 
weapons program 
i cannot certify to you today or to the public that we know 
exactly what is contained in radioactive waste stored at rocky 
flats he said it will take another four months to revalidate 
the contents of the waste he added 
watkins also defended president bushs decision to nominate 
victor stello as assistant secretary for defense programs the top 
job in the weapons program despite what watkins called the 
potential controversiality of the choice 
in 1987 a senate panel conducted a hearing on whether stello as 
executive director for operations of the nuclear regulatory 
commission was guilty of improprieties in connection with a 
commission investigation of the tennessee valley authority 
the probe included the question of whether stello improperly 
advised the manager of nuclear power at tva on how to respond to a 
commission inquiry about the readiness of a plant under 
construction stello denied any improprieties 
if he has some chinks in his armour so be it watkins said 
i have to have somebody in here who wants to serve and let me 
tell you not many want in on this one and has the skills and 
background to understand from day one what it means to run a 
reactor 
</TEXT>
