<TEXT>
the house on tuesday approved plans to require 
the government to collect and publish for five years statistics on 
crimes based on the race ethic group sexual preference or religion 
of the victims 
this legislation is an opportunity to begin the counterattack 
against crimes based on hate said rep charles e schumer 
dny as the house approved the measure 36847 and sent it to the 
senate 
supporters said the nation is being hit by a growing wave of 
socalled hate crimes ranging from gang attacks on members of 
minority groups to cross burnings and the spray painting of 
swastikas and bigoted slogans 
under the bill statistics would be collected on homicide 
assault robbery burglary theft arson vandalism trespassing 
threats and others deemed appropriate by the justice department if 
they involved bias involving race ethnicity sexual preference or 
religion 
the house has passed similar measures in the past but the senate 
has not acted a hate crimes bill was approved by the senate 
judiciary committee on march 9 and supporters are hoping for a floor 
vote 
the fbi publishes annual crime statistics but does not include 
hate crimes supporters have relied on unofficial reports and 
anecdotal information from news accounts in estimating that the 
problem is growing worse 
rep bill green rny said 1281 antisemitic incidents were 
reported by the antidefamation league of bnai brith in 1988 he 
said the national gay and lesbian task force reported 7008 
incidents of antigay violence in 1987 there is also evidence of 
growing klan neonazi skinhead and other hate group activity 
throughout the nation green said 
the tremendous rise in crimes against minorities is widespread 
and extremely serious rep nancy pelosi dcalif said 
compiling data on such acts would help in fighting them 
supporters said the more we know about crimes of hate the more 
chance we have of preventing them said rep barbara b kennelly 
dconn 
congress should send a clear signal to all people that crimes 
based on race religion or sexuality will not be tolerated said 
rep ben gilman rny 
</TEXT>
