<DOCNO> AP890627-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
there are more than balmy breezes 
blowing from the south 
hundreds of sweettalking scam operators are working the 
telephones to con victims out of a few hundred dollars or in some 
cases their life savings 
investigators estimate 90 percent of all the major boiler 
room telemarketing schemes in the nation are based in either south 
florida or southern california with affluent orange county calif 
dethroning fort lauderdale several years ago as the countrys scam 
capital 
the pitches are limited only by the imagination from oil wells 
to medical breakthroughs worm ranches to lowcost precious metals 
and rope in nearly 1 billion annually according to the federal 
trade commission 
officials say the best salesmen can mold a lump of truth into a 
monument of credibility and disguise a sham as a onceinalifetime 
deal 
these boiler room guys like life in the fast lane the yachts 
the fancy cars the sunshine said kent neal head of the broward 
county economic crime unit based in fort lauderdale south florida 
and southern california offer the kind of lifestyle they want 
scam artists also like southern climes for their transient 
populations and ready pools of pitchmen 
some of the ads they run specifically target struggling actors 
or musicians said david katz coordinator of the southern 
california fraud task force based in los angeles in an way its 
like an acting job they try to give the pitch as sincerely and 
convincingly as possible too many times it works 
tougher state laws and more aggressive enforcement have driven 
many boiler room operators from the fort lauderdale area but neal 
estimates about 80 large telemarketing fraud operations still carry 
on from miami to palm beach katz said at least 150 boiler rooms 
have staked out southern california with most centered around 
newport beach 
the boiler rooms ability to survive is partially due to lack of 
coordination betwen federal and state law enforcement agencies and 
the con artists nomadic instincts say investigators 
when the law gets too close they pack up shop and begin 
again said deputy state attorney albert sheldon a boiler room 
specialist based in san diego 
the first telephone scams began in south florida in the 1920s 
when salesmen would pitch mosquitoinfested swampland as prime 
property the boiler rooms so called for their typically spartan 
surroundings did not flourish again until the 1970s this time 
surebet oil and gas fields and inexpensive gems and gold dominated 
the pitches said neal 
one of neals favorite souvenirs from the early 80s heyday of 
south florida boiler rooms is a piece of wood carved and painted to 
resemble a gold bar it was found with others in the vaults of 
international gold bullion exchange one of the boldest and most 
notorious fraud scams on record 
from unusually swank offices in a fort lauderdale skyscraper 
topped with the igbe logo principals william and james alderdice 
reportedly made 75 million on fraudulent sales of gold silver and 
platinum to 13000 investors many reassured by igbe ads in the wall 
street journal some igbe salesmen earned 8000 a week and the 
alderdices were known to toss 100 bills from their stretch 
limousine and watch folks scramble for the cash 
neals successful prosecution of igbe in 1985 was the first major 
boiler room case in south florida and is credited with beginning the 
crackdown that drove many to california william alderdice was 
hacked to death by his chauffeur before the trial began and his 
brother received a 10year federal and a sixyear state sentence 
we are an equal opportunity agency we prosecute anyone we 
have doctors lawyers and indian chiefs neal said pointing to a 
photo of bernard kabrahrah a former comanche tribal leader who 
became involved in a 40 million scam to sell rights to 
nonproducing natural gas wells in oklahoma 
and the victims known as mooches or mullets in boilerroom 
parlance are just as varied 
its no longer just the retirees getting burned yuppies with 
money to spend are becoming the new targets said neal 
some emerging scams include bogus job search agencies travel 
club ripoffs and touting lowpriced penny stocks according to 
the alliance against fraud in telemarketing a watchdog group neal 
has also noticed organized crime taking an interest in boiler rooms 
in april the securities and exchange commission charged the 
nations largest penny stock dealer stuartjames co inc of 
denver with defrauding clients at its boca raton office by making 
exaggerated claims about companies a good boiler room salesman is 
like a chameleon said neal if you are religious suddenly they 
are bornagain if you have kids they are suddenly the concerned 
parent they tell you what you want to hear 
in southern california scams involving vitamins and prize 
contests are hot say investigators 
the boiler rooms hook customers with a postcard saying they have 
won a valuable prize sometimes cash a car or jewelry the catch 
is that the customers must also purchase a supply of vitamins or 
some other item often the vitamins or prize are never delivered or 
they are grossly inferior to the product described by the yaks 
or boiler room salesmen 
yet local agencies are often slow to crack down said katz 
the cops here are dealing with drug traffic gang violence and 
all sorts of other things said katz whose office has prosecuted 
300 people since 1986 
some areas such as clark county nev have discouraged boiler 
rooms by requiring costly bonds for each company and every employee 
of a telemarking firm 
california began registration of telemarketing firms in january 
1987 and operators face a maximum penalty of one year in prison and 
a 10000 fine for failing to comply 
florida adopted tough boilerroom laws in october 1986 including 
making schemes involving more than 50000 in losses a firstdegree 
felony punishable by up to 30 years in prison in 1987 gary fox was 
convicted of swindling 11 million from 4000 investors in his 
united precious metals firm and was sentenced to 585 years in 
prison believed to be the longest whitecollar crime sentence 
neal has one letter he cant forget it came in early 1987 from 
samuel kaminsky of hazleton pa who lost 70000 in mostly 
borrowed money in the united precious metals scam 
i feel foolish and unable to make decisions i always feel as 
though i will make another devastating mistake wrote kaminsky 
these letters tear me up said neal when a guy robs you on 
the street at least he is up front and only takes what is in your 
pocket with telemarketing scams they dont just take whats in 
your pocket but everything else you own you can make more money 
but its the emotional impact you may never recover from 
</TEXT>
