<TEXT>
sustaining success has been difficult for 
eastman kodak co this decade and thats one reason the companys 
name keeps coming up on wall street as a possible takeover target 
the company has managed to turn around a sagging bottom line 
twice since 1980 only to see the same problems increased 
competition a rising us dollar and higher costs return to chew 
up profits 
it seems like they wipe their brow and say whew were glad 
thats over and they turn around and have to do it all over 
again said mark obenzinger a stock analyst for wood gundy amp co 
in new york 
call it the threeyear twitch 
kodak laid off thousands of workers in 1983 saying unfavorable 
exchange rates and soft markets overseas had hurt its business the 
companys profits went up 63 percent the next year 
in 1986 the company had to lay off more than 10000 workers 
radically restructure the company and start a costcutting program 
in an effort to remain competitive 
profits more than tripled the next year and set a record in 1988 
now in 1989 after profits declined 23 percent in the first 
quarter of the year the company has announced plans to cut costs by 
consolidating its photofinishing and consumer photography units 
which could mean hundreds of layoffs 
it does seem to go in cycles and were at the point where the 
company is under pressure again said eugene glazer a stock 
analyst with dean witter reynolds inc 
meanwhile kodak is having trouble controlling expenses at 
sterling drug co which it bought for 51 billion last year and 
the company is battling in court to prevent a large damage award to 
polaroid corp in the two companies patent infringement lawsuit 
over instant photography 
as if all these problemsthatwontgoaway arent enough kodak 
was named last month as the no 1 emitter of the industrial 
pollutant methylene chloride by a washingtonbased environmental 
group 
analysts point to several reasons for kodaks rollercoaster ride 
through the 80s 
first and foremost is the value of the us dollar 
when the dollar is strong compared to other countries 
currencies kodak gets hurt in two ways its profits overseas are 
smaller when translated back into dollars and foreign rivals gain a 
price advantage in sales to the us market 
this double whammy hurt kodak throughout the first half of the 
decade and helped competitors like fuji photo film co and 
agfagevaert inc loosen kodaks strangle hold on photographic film 
sales around the world 
in the 1970s kodak sold between 90 and 95 percent of all 
photographic film in the world today that has fallen to between 80 
and 85 percent according to industry estimates 
the dollar has been gaining strength for the past year and 
unless it weakens soon kodak is going to have to continue cutting 
costs to offset the losses it will bring 
im not sounding alarm right now on the dollar but im getting 
ready to kodaks chairman colby chandler said if it hasnt 
started down by yearend im going to be concerned 
chandler said its difficult to determine how much of kodaks 
woes can be traced to outside factors like the dollar or to 
management decisions made by kodak executives 
america basically has sort of a chip on its shoulder these 
days were always trying to find whos to blame for something 
chandler said instead of taking responsibility we have learned 
to blame everyone else but ourselves for what goes wrong 
he said he doesnt want kodak to join that chorus 
in an effort to become more in control chandler said the company 
is planning to sell a number of its businesses that have either been 
developed within the company or been acquired 
each one will not make a significant impact on the company or 
the public eye theyre not that big but the idea is very powerful 
inside the company chandler said 
kodak remains a benevolent corporate father figure to the 
rochester area where it remains the largest employer said peter 
enderlin an analyst for smith barney harris upham amp co 
their idea of dramatic costcutting and dramatic restructuring 
really isnt that dramatic enderlin said they still have a 
mentality that is somewhat paternalistic 
questions about kodak being too nice only pump up the takeover 
talk on wall street 
rumors have swirled in the past few weeks speculating that 
corporate raider carl icahn has begun looking at the company and 
that kodak might be considering a merger with general electric co 
with takeovers sweeping corporate america stock analysts arent 
surprised that kodaks name has popped up on the merger and 
acquisitions menu but most agree a takeover of the company is 
unlikely 
these rumors get started because the company has 
characteristics that attract corporate raiders but the odds are 
against a takeover attempt said glazer 
kodak is a wellknown name its in a good industry and its 
being managed for longterm growth three things that appeal to 
corporate raiders who want companies that can be changed around to 
yield more money right away 
i guess there are some people who believe that some outside 
group can wave a magic wand and change kodak from an ugly duckling 
into a beautiful swan said enderlin of smith barney its not 
that easy 
kodaks businesses are complex the company also has a number of 
hurdles that give it some protection from potential hostile 
takeovers 
the company is incorporated in new jersey which has tough 
antitakeover laws if a raider acquired a majority of kodak stock 
management could issue enough new stock to friendly buyers to 
outvote the raider 
the company also has about 13 billion in long and shortterm 
debt which would increase the cost of a leveraged buyout 
nothings impossible but a takeover attempt would be hard to 
believe said obenzinger 
</TEXT>
