<TEXT>
the bush administration will be forced to 
double its initial spending on savings and loan rescues if congress 
restricts the financial power of the new sampl bailout agency thrift 
regulator m danny wall said tuesday 
if a congressional conference committee next month adopts the 
house version of the sampl bill wall said the new agency called the 
resolution trust corp would need to spend at least twice the 50 
billion it is due to receive over the next three years 
the house bill unlike the senate version forbids the bailout 
agency from issuing promissory notes or loss guarantees extending 
its liability beyond the 50 billion 
wall speaking at a conference of the us league of saving 
institutions the industrys largest trade group said 50 billion 
represents the net cost of closing and merging insolvent thrifts it 
reflects the cost after the government recovers some of its expenses 
by selling real estate inherited from failed sampls he said 
unless the agency can rescue institutions by issuing promissory 
notes and paying them off years later after the government sells the 
real estate the initial cash outlay needed will be at least 100 
billion he said 
in that case president bush would be forced to ask congress in 
several years for more money 
rep henry b gonzalez dtexas chairman of the house banking 
committee insisted on the restriction arguing that walls agency 
the federal home loan bank board abused its notewriting powers 
last year and in effect spent money without congressional approval 
he has said he wants to ensure the resolution trust corp which 
will take over some of the bank boards duties will not have 
similar leeway 
wall also complained about another provision in the house bill 
that makes the federal deposit insurance corp the primary regulator 
of statechartered sampls taking away that power from the agency that 
will succeed the bank board walls agency under the senate 
version retains its power over both state and federal sampls 
wall said that would create conflicts of interest in the future 
because the fdic as the insuror of sampl deposits likely will become 
partowner of rescued institutions the fdic should not regulate 
institutions it owns while at the same time regulating privately 
owned competing institutions he said 
on another topic wall said both the house and senate sampl bills 
do not give his agency and the fdic enough power to allow 
capitaldeficient savings and loans to continue operating 
wall said that even advocates of very tough capital rules believe 
regulators ought to have the leeway to allow undercapitalized sampls 
to continue operating provided they are profitable have competent 
managers and stick to a plan to increase their capital 
however a recent review by bank board lawyers indicates that 
regulators do not have enough authority to grant that leeway 
theres too much pressure to say no and not enough ability to 
say yes he said 
